<paragraph blockId="12.[160,1156,1588,1717]" box="[160,409,1588,1614]" pageId="12" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,409,1588,1614]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="277">External morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[160,1156,1588,1717]" pageId="12" pageNumber="277">Body short, thick, background colour white with numerous black and yellow dots. Rhinophores lamellar, protected by two papillae, the posterior one longer than those anterior. Gill leaves discoid in shape, protected by long posterior papillae.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="278" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[159,1156,142,237]" box="[160,252,142,168]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,252,142,168]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[159,1156,142,237]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">
The singleton specimen was found on an unidentified bryozoan species of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1076,1149,178,203]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Bugulidae" genus="Bugula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1076,1149,178,203]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Bugula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The species is nocturnal; during the day slugs are found ‘resting’ at the base of bryozoans.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="278" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[160,1156,297,461]" box="[160,300,297,323]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,300,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[160,1156,297,461]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">
Originally described from the North Sea (
<collectingCountry box="[643,739,332,357]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">England</collectingCountry>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Montagu G" box="[753,921,332,357]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" pagination="1 - 26" refId="ref20936" refString="Montagu G. 1813. Descriptions of several new or rare animals, principally marine, discovered on the South coast of Devonshire. Trans Linn Soc London. 11: 1 - 26. doi: 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1813. tb 00035. x." type="journal article" year="1813">Montagu 1813</bibRefCitation>
); 
<collectingRegion box="[945,1152,332,357]" country="Australia" name="New South Wales" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">New South Wales</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[160,260,367,392]" name="Australia" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Burn R" box="[278,401,367,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" pagination="22" refId="ref18386" refString="Burn R. 1978. A new record of Thecacera pennigera (Montagu, 1815) (Opisthobranchia: Polycerldae) from New South Wales. J Malacol Soc Aust. 4: 22. doi: 10.1080 / 00852988.1978.10673905." type="journal article" year="1978">Burn 1978</bibRefCitation>
); south-west coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[672,728,367,392]" name="India" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">India</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mohamed Hatha AA" box="[746,1012,367,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" pagination="222 - 224" refId="ref20712" refString="Mohamed Hatha AA. 2017. First record of the alien sea slug Thecacera pennigera (Montagu, 1813) (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Nudibranchia: Polyceridae) from southwest coast of India. J Aquatic Biol Fish. 5: 222 - 224." type="journal article" year="2017">Mohamed Hatha 2017</bibRefCitation>
); north-east American coast, 
<collectingCountry box="[348,443,402,427]" name="Portugal" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Portugal</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[502,549,402,427]" name="Italy" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Italy</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gerovasileiou V &amp; Akel EHK &amp; Akyol O &amp; Alongi G &amp; Azevedo F" box="[563,843,402,427]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" pagination="355 - 384" refId="ref19830" refString="Gerovasileiou V, Akel EHK, Akyol O, Alongi G, Azevedo F, et al. 2017. New Mediterranean Biodiversity Records (July 2017). Mediterr Mar Sci. 18: 355 - 384. doi: 10.12681 / mms. 13771." type="journal article" year="2017">Gerovasileiou et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bariche M &amp; Al-Mabruk SAA &amp; Ates MA &amp; Buyuk A &amp; Crocetta F &amp; Dritsas M &amp; Edde D &amp; Fortic A &amp; Gavriil E &amp; Gerovasileiou V" box="[857,1066,402,427]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" pagination="129 - 145" refId="ref18116" refString="Bariche M, Al-Mabruk SAA, Ates MA, Buyuk A, Crocetta F, Dritsas M, Edde D, Fortic A, Gavriil E, Gerovasileiou V 2020. New Alien Mediterranean Biodiversity Records. Mediterr Mar Sci. 21: 129 - 145. doi: 10.12681 / mms. 21987." type="journal article" year="2020">Bariche et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
); 
<collectingCountry box="[1087,1152,402,427]" name="Spain" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Spain</collectingCountry>
: the 
<collectingRegion box="[204,368,436,461]" country="Spain" name="Canarias" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Canary Islands</collectingRegion>
, Cantabric Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Cervera JL &amp; Calado G &amp; Gavaia C &amp; Malaquias MAE &amp; Templado J &amp; Ballesteros M &amp; Megina C &amp; Garcia-Gomez JC" box="[545,757,436,461]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" pagination="5 - 111" refId="ref18631" refString="Cervera JL, Calado G, Gavaia C, Malaquias MAE, Templado J, Ballesteros M, Megina C, Garcia-Gomez JC. 2004. An annotated and updated checklist of the opisthobranchs (Mollusca: Gastropoda) from Spain and Portugal (including Islands and archipelagos). Boletin-Instituto Espanol de Oceanografia. 20: 5 - 111." type="journal article" year="2004">Cervera et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingRegion box="[777,882,436,461]" country="Spain" name="Catalunya" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Catalonia</collectingRegion>
