</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="278" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[160,1156,521,685]" box="[160,262,521,547]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,521,547]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[160,1156,521,685]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">
This species has a broad distribution and is usually found in temperate waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Dekker R" box="[166,315,591,616]" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" pagination="45 - 46" refId="ref19080" refString="Dekker R. 1986. Second record of Thecacera pennigera (Gastropoda: Opisthobranchia) from the Dutch coast. Basteria. 50: 45 - 46." type="journal article" year="1986">Dekker 1986</bibRefCitation>
). In the western Atlantic, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Montagu" baseAuthorityYear="1813" box="[628,769,591,616]" class="Gastropoda" family="Polyceridae" genus="Thecacera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pennigera">
<emphasis box="[628,769,591,616]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="278">T. pennigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has peaks of abundance during which, over the course of a few days, large numbers of specimens appear (
<bibRefCitation author="Willan RC &amp; Coleman N" pageId="13" pageNumber="278" refId="ref23089" refString="Willan RC, and Coleman N. 1984.. Nudibranchs of Australasia (Syndey, Australia: Sea Australian Productions Ltd.). 56." type="book" year="1984">Willan and Coleman 1984</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
